a></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The two sides have until the fall to define the general contours of a future trade deal. However, many European officials believe it could then require several years of further negotiations in order to flesh out and ratify new trading arrangements between the U.K. and the remaining members of the union.</Para><Para>The completion of the transition and the advance of talks is a boost for U.K. Prime Minister Theresa May, whose precarious political position at home has at times threatened to slow or even upend talks.</Para><Para>"I believe there is a new dynamic now in the negotiations," she said after Friday's summit meeting in Brussels. "We are approaching this with a spirit of cooperation, a spirit of opportunity for the future as well."</Para><Para>However, her government had to make key sacrifices in order to secure a transition that businesses have asked for to have time to prepare for the U.K.'s separation from the EU.</Para><Para>London accepted most of the terms the EU pressed for, including paying a so-called divorce bill of at least £39 billion ($55 billion) in order to settle past financial commitments the U.K. ​has made while a member of the bloc. It has also made politically painful promises to avoid a hard border on the island of Ireland.</Para><Para>During the transition, Britain will lose its vote in the union but must abide by its rules and regulations and will be subject to EU court decisions. EU citizens who arrive in Britain during the transition will continue to enjoy the possibility of eventually winning permanent residency.</Para><Para>The guidelines for the trade talks, say EU negotiators, should aim for an agreement that would include zero tariffs across goods and agricultural trade. But EU officials say this arrangement would require controls at the border because the frictionless trade the U.K. says it wants is incompatible with the U.K.​'s aim of taking back control of key EU rules and exiting​the bloc's internal market and customs union.</Para><Para>​Future trade arrangements will focus on agreeing "a very intensive free-trade agreement," said German Chancellor Angela Merkel Friday.</Para><Para>European officials have warned that Britain can't expect to secure special deals for key sectors such as auto manufacturers, financial services and airlines to the EU's single market.</Para><Para>"The single market can't be carved out. Once you're out, you're out of all sectors," said French President Emmanuel Macron.</Para><Para>Yet there are signs the coming months could strain EU unity and could complicate the talks. Some countries, for instance, have signaled their desire to maintain closer ties with the U.K. after Brexit.</Para><Para>Luxembourg officials sought more flexible language on financial services, which British officials hope might give London the ability to influence EU decisions on whether to recognize British financial rules and regulation as equivalent to those of the EU. London has been keen to safeguard the U.K.'s status as a major financial center.</Para><Para>​Meanwhile, Mrs. May faces political tensions at home that could render a deal more difficult. Her party lacks a parliamentary majority and pro-Brexit lawmakers are pressing for concessions on issues including fish quotas and the size of the divorce bill.</Para><Para>Jenny Gross and William Horobin contributed to this article.</Para><Para>Write to Laurence Norman at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com">laurence.norman@wsj.com</ELink> and Valentina Pop at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:valentina.pop@wsj.com">valentina.pop@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Laurence Norman and Valentina Pop </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All